# Project-wide ShellCheck configuration (developer / local scope)
# See: https://www.shellcheck.net/wiki/Directive
#
# CI / Trunk uses a separate config at .trunk/configs/.shellcheckrc which sets
# enable=all (surfacing optional/style checks). Running `shellcheck` directly
# will therefore produce fewer warnings than `trunk check`. Use
# `trunk check <file>` to reproduce full CI output locally.
#
# This file centralises intentional, policy-level exclusions so that inline
# `# shellcheck disable=` annotations can be reserved for one-off, site-specific
# suppressions that need their own rationale.
#
# Guidelines:
#   • Only exclude codes whose suppression is *project policy* (not a bug being hidden).
#   • Each entry MUST have a comment explaining WHY it is excluded and what the
#     acceptable alternative looks like.
#   • Real-bug warnings (SC2155, SC2086, SC2046, …) are NOT silenced here; they
#     must be fixed at the call site or suppressed inline with a justification.

# SC1091: Not following sourced files.
# Rationale: The codebase uses a dynamic sourcing pattern where paths are computed
# at runtime (e.g. source "$LIB_DIR/foo.sh" or source "${SCRIPT_DIR}/lib/common.sh").
# ShellCheck cannot statically resolve these paths, so every sourced library triggers
# SC1091. All sourced files are version-controlled in this repo; the warning adds no
# value project-wide.
# Acceptable alternative: use `# shellcheck source=path/to/file` at specific call
# sites when static analysis of the sourced content is genuinely needed.
disable=SC1091

# SC1090: ShellCheck can't follow non-constant source.
# Rationale: Same dynamic-sourcing pattern as SC1091. Many scripts construct the
# source path via variables (e.g. source "${SCRIPT_DIR}/lib/common.sh" or
# source "$LIB_DIR/utils.sh"). This is intentional and safe; the files are always
# present in the repo.
# Acceptable alternative: use `# shellcheck source=…` inline where the sourced
# file's interface needs to be visible to static analysis.
disable=SC1090

# SC2034: Variable appears unused.
# NOTE: intentionally kept commented-out. Many color/emoji constants and
# configuration variables are exported for consumption by child processes
# (e.g. RED, GREEN, E_PASS). However, SC2034 also catches genuine unused locals
# that should be cleaned up, so the warning remains visible project-wide.
# Re-evaluate once the variable audit in issue #446 is complete.
# disable=SC2034
